# Improving Medicaid While Delivering Cost Effectiveness: A Comprehensive Analysis

Medicaid, a vital public health insurance program in the United States, covers nearly one in five Americans, including low-income adults, children, pregnant women, older adults, and people with disabilities. It accounts for almost 30% of total state spending, making cost containment a critical policy goal for states ([National Conference of State Legislatures, 2021](https://www.ncsl.org/research/health/improving-health-and-controlling-costs-in-medicaid-the-6-18-initiative.aspx)). Despite its importance, Medicaid faces persistent challenges related to rising costs, high prevalence of chronic conditions among enrollees, and the need to improve health outcomes efficiently. This report provides an in-depth, evidence-based analysis of strategies to improve Medicaid while achieving cost effectiveness, drawing on recent research, federal initiatives, and state-level innovations.

---

## 1. Context and Challenges in Medicaid Cost and Quality Management

Medicaid serves a disproportionately high-risk population with complex health needs, including chronic diseases such as diabetes, asthma, and hypertension. These conditions are among the most costly to treat and manage, contributing significantly to Medicaid expenditures ([National Conference of State Legislatures, 2021](https://www.ncsl.org/research/health/improving-health-and-controlling-costs-in-medicaid-the-6-18-initiative.aspx)).

Historically, Medicaid operated under a fee-for-service (FFS) payment model, which incentivized volume over value, often leading to inefficiencies and fragmented care. Since the 1980s, there has been a gradual shift toward managed care and value-based payment models aimed at improving care coordination, quality, and cost control ([Annual Review of Public Health, 2020](https://www.annualreviews.org/doi/10.1146/annurev-publhealth-040119-094345)).

Despite these reforms, evidence on cost savings remains mixed. Some studies report modest savings and quality improvements in specific states or populations, while others find limited or no cost reductions at the national level ([Annual Review of Public Health, 2020](https://www.annualreviews.org/doi/10.1146/annurev-publhealth-040119-094345)). This variability underscores the need for targeted, evidence-based strategies tailored to Medicaid’s unique population and state contexts.

---

## 2. The CDC’s 6|18 Initiative: Targeting High-Burden Conditions with Evidence-Based Interventions

A promising approach to improving Medicaid cost effectiveness is the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention’s (CDC) 6|18 Initiative. This initiative focuses on six common, preventable health conditions—tobacco use, high blood pressure, inappropriate antibiotic use, asthma, unintended pregnancies, and type 2 diabetes—and 18 evidence-based interventions that have demonstrated health and cost benefits within 18 months of implementation ([CDC, 2021](https://www.ncsl.org/research/health/improving-health-and-controlling-costs-in-medicaid-the-6-18-initiative.aspx)).

### Key Features of the 6|18 Initiative:

| Condition           | Examples of Evidence-Based Interventions                          | Potential Impact                                  |
|---------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------------|
| Tobacco Use         | Tobacco cessation counseling, nicotine replacement therapy       | Reduced smoking rates, decreased healthcare costs |
| High Blood Pressure | Hypertension screening, medication adherence programs            | Lower incidence of cardiovascular events        |
| Inappropriate Antibiotic Use | Provider education, prescribing guidelines                      | Reduced antibiotic resistance and costs          |
| Asthma              | Asthma action plans, environmental trigger reduction             | Fewer emergency visits and hospitalizations      |
| Unintended Pregnancies | Access to long-acting reversible contraception (LARC)           | Reduced unintended pregnancies and associated costs |
| Type 2 Diabetes     | Diabetes self-management education, medication adherence          | Improved glycemic control, reduced complications |

The 6|18 Initiative has engaged over 40 state, local, and territorial Medicaid and public health teams, facilitating collaboration, technical assistance, and peer learning to implement these interventions effectively ([CDC, 2021](https://www.ncsl.org/research/health/improving-health-and-controlling-costs-in-medicaid-the-6-18-initiative.aspx)).

