## 3. Delivery System and Payment Reforms: Shifting from Volume to Value

State Medicaid programs have increasingly adopted delivery system and payment reforms to align incentives with quality and cost outcomes. Common models include:

- **Managed Care Organizations (MCOs):** As of 2019, 33 states reported that 75% or more of Medicaid beneficiaries were enrolled in risk-based MCOs, which integrate behavioral and physical health services and incorporate quality incentives such as pay-for-performance (P4P) ([Kaiser Family Foundation, 2022](https://www.kff.org/medicaid/issue-brief/state-delivery-system-and-payment-strategies-aimed-at-improving-outcomes-and-lowering-costs-in-medicaid/)).

- **Patient-Centered Medical Homes (PCMHs):** These models emphasize coordinated, comprehensive primary care with a focus on prevention and chronic disease management.

- **Accountable Care Organizations (ACOs):** Medicaid ACOs hold providers accountable for cost and quality across a population. Early evidence from states like Colorado, Minnesota, Oregon, and Vermont shows promising cost savings and quality improvements, including $77 million net savings in Colorado over four years and a 23% reduction in emergency department visits in Oregon ([National Conference of State Legislatures, 2016](https://www.ncsl.org/research/health/accountable-care-organizations-health-costs.aspx)).

- **Episodes of Care and Global Budgets:** Emerging payment models that bundle payments for episodes of care or set global budgets to incentivize efficiency.

### Payment Model Spectrum and Provider Risk

| Payment Model Type                     | Provider Financial Risk | Incentive Focus                         |
|--------------------------------------|------------------------|---------------------------------------|
| Fee-for-Service (FFS)                 | None                   | Volume of services                    |
| Pay-for-Performance (P4P)             | Low                    | Quality and efficiency bonuses       |
| Shared Savings (One-sided Risk)       | Moderate               | Savings sharing without penalties    |
| Shared Risk (Two-sided Risk)           | High                   | Savings sharing and penalties for losses |
| Global Capitation                     | Very High              | Fixed payment for all care            |

States are increasingly incorporating Alternative Payment Models (APMs) in managed care contracts to encourage value-based care, though the impact varies by state and model maturity ([Kaiser Family Foundation, 2022](https://www.kff.org/medicaid/issue-brief/state-delivery-system-and-payment-strategies-aimed-at-improving-outcomes-and-lowering-costs-in-medicaid/)).

